class Solution {
    public List<List<Integer>> combine(int n, int k) {
        List<List<Integer>> res = new ArrayList<>();
        backtrack(res, new ArrayList<>(), 1, n, k);
        return res;
    }

    private void backtrack(List<List<Integer>> res, List<Integer> cur, int start, int n, int k) {
        if (k == 0) {
            res.add(new ArrayList<>(cur));
            return;
        }
        for (int i = start; i <= n - k + 1; i++) {
            cur.add(i);
            backtrack(res, cur, i + 1, n, k - 1);
            cur.remove(cur.size() - 1);
        }
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(C(n,k) * k)
space complexity: O(k)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses backtracking with pruning to generate combinations in lexicographic order. The loop bound n-k+1 avoids unnecessary recursive calls, ensuring only valid combinations are built.

